## Relay-A2 Checkpoint & State Persistence
**Status:** draft
**Tags:** stack:backend
**Depends on:** Runtime-G1

JSON provides human-readable, version-controllable checkpoints. Git auto-commits provide a robust file-level rollback mechanism that integrates with existing developer workflows. The Ledger is embedded (not referenced) to ensure self-contained checkpoints.

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Handoff Triggered] --> B[Capture File Manifest]
    B --> C[Git Commit or Diff]
    C --> D[Serialize Ledger]
    D --> E[Write Handoff Document]
    E --> F[Write Checkpoint JSON]
    F --> G[Update Run Store]
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| JSON + git | Human-readable, git-native rollback, simple | Large checkpoints for big projects |
| SQLite + binary blobs | Compact, queryable | Harder to inspect, git-unfriendly |
| Content-addressed store (IPFS-style) | Deduplication, immutable | Overkill for local orchestration |

- Positive: Checkpoints can be inspected with `cat` or `jq`.
- Positive: Rollback uses standard git commands.
- Negative: Large projects may produce multi-MB checkpoint files.
- Mitigation: File manifest stores hashes, not contents. Only changed files are diffed.

